## YOUTUBE DESCRIPTION

For 2,500 years, scholars have claimed that Hindu Moksha and Buddhist Nirvana are the same liberation described differently. But the truth is far more controversial: **they're almost completely opposite goals.**

Moksha = eternal union with infinite divine consciousness (ƒÅtman merges with Brahman, consciousness continues forever)

Nirvana = the complete cessation of the illusion of self (craving and ignorance end; consciousness doesn't continue)

In this video, we explore why both traditions have fundamentally contradictory understandings of what "liberation" even means‚Äîand why neither religion is happy about the other's definition. From the Buddha's explicit rejection of Brahman, to Shankara's critique of Buddhist "nihilism," to modern confusion in the spiritual marketplace, this is the philosophical opposition that academic syncretism tries to smooth over but can't.

